  <p>
    <alert>Definition 1</alert>
    Sets are important to the study of probability.
    An <em>experiment</em> is an action we take and its result is called
    the <em>outcome</em>. For example, we can have an experiment which is flipping
    a coin and recording which side comes up. The possible outcomes are
    <m>1, \ldots, 6</m>. The set of all possible outcomes of an experiment
    is called the <em>sample space</em>.
  </p>
  <p>
    <row><alert>Example</alert></row>
    1. 
    Say we flip a coin three times in a row and note the result of each flip.
    Then our sample space is
    <me> S=\{HHH,HHT,HTH,HTT,THH,THT,TTH,TTT\}.</me>
  </p>
  <p>
    2.
    If our experiment is flipping a coin and then rolling a four-sided die,
    our sample space is
    <me> S=\{H1, H2, H3, H4, T1, T2, T3, T4\}.</me>
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>Definition 2</alert>
    It is often useful to represent small experiments visually.
    We use <em>tree diagrams</em> to do so.
    The results of each stage are represented by using the forks and branches of the tree.
    Each path through the tree (from left to right as pictured below) represents
    the results of all stages of the experiment and therefore is one possible outcome of the experiment.
  </p>
  <p>
    This visualization provides a systematic way to identify all possible outcomes of the experiment.
    In particular, it can help us avoid accidentally omitting any of the possible outcomes.
  </p>

