  <p>
    <alert>Question:</alert>
    An experiment consists of picking out an outfit for the day. We have three choices of shirt: green, black,
and blue. We have two choices of pants: white and red. Draw a tree diagram for this experiment and state
the sample space.
  </p>
  <p>
    <alert>Definition 3</alert>
    Note that our choice of pants didn’t depend on our choice of
    shirt. For each choice of shirt, we had two choices of pants. So there were <m>3\cdot 2 = 6</m>
    outcomes in our sample
    space. This hold whenever our stages are independent.
    This is called the <em>multiplication principle</em>.
    Suppose we have a <m>k</m> stage experiement where each stage is independent of the others. Then
    <me>|S| = n_1 \cdot n_2 \cdots n_k,</me>
    where <m>n_i</m> is the number of results in stage <m>i</m> and <m>|S|</m> denotes the size
    of the set <m>S</m>, which represents our sample space.
  </p>

